            <div class="post-bg" style="padding:15px;">
				  <p id="breadcrumbs">You are here: <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.drmercola.biz/">Home</a> &raquo; <a href="http://www.drmercola.biz/health-articles/">Health Articles</a> &raquo; <a href="http://www.drmercola.biz/category/healthy-food/">Healthy Food</a> &raquo; <strong>Dr. Mercola Talks About the Benefits of Dark Chocolate</strong></p>    
				<h1 class="title"><a href="http://www.drmercola.biz/healthy-food/dr-mercola-talks-about-the-benefits-of-dark-chocolate/" rel="bookmark" title="Permanent Link to Dr. Mercola Talks About the Benefits of Dark Chocolate">Dr. Mercola Talks About the Benefits of Dark Chocolate</a></h1>
                <p class="meta">Posted on October 7th, 2011 by author &nbsp;|&nbsp;   <a href="http://www.drmercola.biz/healthy-food/dr-mercola-talks-about-the-benefits-of-dark-chocolate/#comments" title="Comment on Dr. Mercola Talks About the Benefits of Dark Chocolate">1 Comment &#187;</a></p>
				<div class="entry">

				<p><a href="http://www.drmercola.biz/healthy-food/dr-mercola-talks-about-the-benefits-of-dark-chocolate/attachment/dark-chocolate-benefits-your-health/" rel="attachment wp-att-636"><img class="alignright size-full wp-image-636" title="dark chocolate benefits your health" src="http://www.drmercola.biz/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/dark-chocolate-benefits-your-health.jpg" alt="dark chocolate benefits your health" width="250" height="250" /></a>Hereâ€™s great news for chocoholics: Eating <a href="http://articles.mercola.com/sites/articles/archive/2011/09/21/can-eating-this-sweet-treat-decrease-risk-of-the-1-cause-of-death.aspx"><strong>organic and unprocessed dark chocolate</strong></a> may help you avoid cardiovascular risks. A recent meta-analysis evaluated the link between chocolate and cardiometabolic disorders, which are certain risk factors that promote the development of stroke, coronary heart disease, and type 2 diabetes. Examples of cardiometabolic disorders include:</p>
<ul>
<li>Hypertension</li>
<li>Elevated fasting glucose</li>
<li>High cholesterol levels</li>
<li>Abdominal obesity</li>
<li>Elevated triglycerides</li>
</ul>
<p>The results of seven studies, which collectively included over 114,000 participants, were used for the featured analysis. Five out of the seven studies confirmed that chocolate can reduce the risk of cardiometabolic disorders. The highest levels of chocolate consumption were linked to a 37 percent reduction in cardiovascular disease and a 29 percent reduction in stroke. (<a href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21875885" target="_blank">link</a>)</p>
<p><a href="http://www.mercola.com/"><strong>Dr. Joseph Mercola</strong> </a>agrees with these findings, but warns that the health benefits only come from unprocessed chocolate and/or raw cacao and not commercially-processed milk chocolate candy bars.</p>
<p><strong>How Raw Chocolate Benefits Your Health</strong></p>
<p>Chocolateâ€™s benefits to your health have been known for a long time. Dr. Mercola says that five years ago, researchers found out that small amounts of dark chocolate can reduce your risk of heart attack. This is because of its biochemical effect â€“ similar to aspirin â€“ that reduces blood clot-causing platelets. If a formed clot blocks a blood vessel, it can be fatal and may cause a heart attack.</p>
<p>Another 2008 study revealed that diabetics can benefit from specially-formulated raw cocoa powder. For one month, diabetic patients were given a special, high-flavonol cocoa drink, which helped turn their severely impaired blood vessel function to normal. Dr. Mercola notes that the improvement was similar to the effect of exercise and regular diabetic medications.</p>
<p>The flavonoid epicathechin, which is found in dark chocolate, may also help protect your brain after a stroke (<a href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20442725" target="_blank">link</a>). Epicathechin increases cellular signals that protect nerve cells from damage. A stroke is similar to a heart attack, except that it occurs when the blood supply to your brain, not your heart, is blocked or reduced. This deprives your brain of necessary oxygen and nutrients, prompting your brain cells to die within minutes.</p>
<p><strong>Choosing a Healthy Type of Chocolate</strong></p>
<p>Keep in mind that the healthful antioxidants and nutrients in chocolate are only present in <strong>pure cocoa</strong>. This means that every time you process the cocoa, the nutritional value is lost. This is why Dr. Mercola says that the best chocolate is bitter, not sweet.</p>
<p>Raw cocoa powder has high antioxidant content. According to a 2003 study in the<em> Journal of Agricultural and Food Chemistry</em>, a cup of hot cocoa made with pure cocoa powder contains</p>
<ul>
<li>Almost twice the amount of antioxidants than a glass of red win</li>
<li>More than double the amount of green tea</li>
<li>Four to five times more than black tea (<a href="http://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2003/11/031106051159.htm" target="_blank">link</a>)</li>
</ul>
<p>Another study published in the journal says that after pure cocoa powder, the best types of chocolate with healthful antioxidants are unsweetened baking chocolate, dark chocolate, and semi-sweet chocolate. (<a href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed?term=%22Journal+of+agricultural+and+food+chemistry%22%5BJour%5D+AND+2009%5Bpdat%5D+AND+Stuart+D%5Bauthor%5D" target="_blank">link</a>)</p>
<p>Dr. Mercola says milk chocolate should be avoided, because aside from having low antioxidant content, the milk in it cancels out the antioxidantsâ€™ effects. Milk chocolate is also loaded with sugar that might do more harm than good to your cardiovascular health.</p>
<p>To ensure getting health benefits from dark chocolate, stick to<strong> USDA Certified Organic chocolate</strong>. The ideal amount of dark chocolate you should consume is less than seven grams daily (less than half a bar a week). If you ingest more than this amount, the benefits may be cancelled out.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
               
